At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange switched to the negative
After Tuesday morning’s fall, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague stock market returned to its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on the Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the American financial sector, is thus also perceptible here.
Stock loss in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even if the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later it cleared some of the losses and reduced the decline to almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares in the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares in the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but ultimately reduced losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“Hesitation about rescue action in the US will influence financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, the head of Hong Kong’s monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates have the same level in Hong Kong as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodshed of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the proposed support of the financial system, to which it should have spent up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 billions of Kč).
Lawmakers are thus denying the call for support of President George Bush's plan.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major equity indices experienced the biggest drop in the past 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost nearly seven percent, having fallen on such a scale for the last time in 1987.
The clue was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress ceded: US government can inject 700 billion dollars into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement to the US financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a turning point in talks on the adoption of a bailout in the form of 700 billion dollars (about 12 trillion crown) financial aid granted to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not safe.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, the Congressmans must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be submitted to the Senate vote.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market aid can be effective, will follow a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on the form that the package of measures for market stabilization should have," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be made as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial companies the unsaleable real estate assets that drive financial firms into considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system in its entirety.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must be, too, effective in the market.
We still have to continue this market recovery plan, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are making Congress reach a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first hourly zone, where Congress’s decision could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for the moment, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two Houses of the American Congress will proceed to the vote, nor if the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will undergo many more changes.
The total amount for the system must be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion dollars, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress will have the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility to block the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first 100 billion dollars more, then, finally, 350 billion dollars.
M. Bush welcomed progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put it in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finances for the redemption of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed on Sunday to vote on the law, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President George Bush is himself pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr. Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated “the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, protection of contributors from losses, the relief agreement, the course of the plan on the time axis.
The new law also provides for the limitation of the said golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will supervise the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and have made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for property owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new down payments in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing debtors to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its achievement is going to be very difficult.
"And this is because we do not know what the mechanism and the price of the buyback of problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive to decide on the division of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week at iHNed.cz.
If the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is not that important, according to Marek.
“It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they will support this plan and dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek said.
Three sights of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly significant losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthie Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to the preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the vote, the country's first political force, however, compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent loses nearly nine percent of the vote, ended even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the People's Party, which called for early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Again in early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the popular party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
However, the voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the leader of the party and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer, was pronounced.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the party leadership.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the grand coalition SPÖ and ÖVP.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the people's party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ parted from it) on a common government
Haider, who has previously said that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he foresees the return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently bets on this development.
The last party to have access to parliament being the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell, among the Austrian political parties, from the third in fifth place.
Obviously, no other party crosses the four percent limit and has reached parliament.
