A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we are still missing something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, many times, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher with us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than the country's customers to select customers.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no more room for another operator, is making a chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently not much luck (by the way, now, it would only find frequencies difficult).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which conventional operators must subsequently also react.
Yet, even before the entry of troublemakers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among other things the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be efficient, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, free from the costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network, which are relatively high.
This is how virtual operators in the world loom as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half the cost of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area,” said Jana Studničková, spokesman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of enterprise customers, has not hidden, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
The sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Perhaps the future is promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"Right now, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific markets.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us,” said Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefonika O2 press department, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
"It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone is directing his attention to completing requests to get his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most contributions from the customer perspective.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities: in line with the operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a fall in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to hear themselves as the thiefs at a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, when the U:fon was created by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon lends itself to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition in the mobile market has also been, in addition, recently amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high requirements.
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties has a priori not presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not surprise the part of the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care, that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
“Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a fall in mobile telephone prices.”
However, lobbying for the honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not part of the interests of ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not noticed any signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for its market behaviour.
The tools necessary to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different vision of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Bringing down responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, by means of which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to pass on the novelization of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an expansion of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
That, the representatives of ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one is looking, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but the latter are only public in part.
In most cases, it is about firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company is in front of the operator figure of a classic corporate customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price offers (and others).
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If it happened what you are talking about, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and that could lead to a stoppage of collaboration with the company in question," replied our question relating to this problem Martina Kemrová.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has reached the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them significant benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to true virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
This is precisely what should seem strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is asked at ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market that was too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries have intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulatory bodies are dealing with this issue in the manner of a warm potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the knock.
If the behind-the-scenes information says it is true and a virtual operator will soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will only be difficult to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choir performance and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to the Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I had been trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that we understood the lyrics well, that they sang simultaneously," he said.
Next year, the Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde domov můj resounded for the first time in 1834 on the stage of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslaovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
