Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about a hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this one will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both register it on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Rozreov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons by internet on the web pages of the Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can definitively forget the ticket offices in the subway stations, where they had until now to trample impatiently in long queues in order to obtain paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon over the internet and will be registered on their Opencard in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these points of contact, there is at the disposal of passengers a ticket office with trained staff, who will help interested parties with the purchase over the internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they have purchased on their card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, it will also be possible to save the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, recall the machines to compost tickets and the passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," added Opatrný.
An automaton will control the coupon in place of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Just introduce the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
Namely in peri-urban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of the Central Bohemia to access the capital.
"In the trains integrated into Pražská integrovaná doprava (built-in transport in Prague), the controllers are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of the coupons;" explained the control of the Filip Drápal tickets of the organization Ropid, which designs the schedules of Prague public transport.
Peri-urban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver’s checkout.
When boarding it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but it is also necessary to place the Opencard at the place indicated on the side of the checkout.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"In case the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing more simple than asking the driver for this information," Drápal said.
Passengers who do not take peri-urban buses and will not remember the date on which their coupon expires, can re-enter the ATMs, which are originally used to save the coupons on the card.
This is where the information about the validity of their document will be displayed on the screen of the device.
The Sudetens were calling for a referendum in the US
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans were allegedly addressed to the President of the United States with such desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American president not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads the letter, signed "Persons, to whom the fate of the Šumava is close to the heart."
Since the rallying of Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without respect, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of the Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter reads.
The so-called reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter can, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Sudeten of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic arose, very few of them confessed to such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetens.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German from České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would be profitable for them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, considered that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
Emotional campaign will attack drivers
Action on the most expensive road safety in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that in order to launch, Wednesday, the Ministry of Transport.
The office of Minister Aleš Řebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast driving and drinking.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the conscience of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also evidenced by the "bloody" slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there is the phrase "You'll pay."
This must symbolize that one can pay for life a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where images can be commonly seen with drastic images of accident victims.
He believes that this will lead to a decrease in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The sugar and whip strategy against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they burn a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers,” said Martin Kořán, the transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and especially negative advertisements, believes the psychologist.
The signs pointing out the danger to drivers are, according to him, already less efficient.
"When a static panel that warns of danger is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will no longer notice it," Kořán said.
Olmert would return in exchange for peace almost all the occupied territories
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli Provisional Government, spoke in favour of the return of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made the statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to make almost all (occupied) or all territories,” Olmert said.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), since without it, peace will not be made," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"He who desires security in Jerusalem, and above all does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert remarked, referring to the two attacks in the city, in July, in which several people were killed and dozens of people wounded.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
"Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270 000 Arabs.
It won’t work,” he said.
Retreat of the Golan Heights
Olmert also supported Israel's retreat from the Golan Heights, which he said was an indispensable condition for concluding a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some efforts on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria only on the basis of a retreat from the Golan," he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they are going to have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with the Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to give up the constant support they give to the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Kaida (terrorist network), as well as that of the Jihad (holy war) in Iraq," said the Prime Minister.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India risk cooling
If the problem concerning the Czech researchers accused in India, accused of illegal gathering of cockroaches could not be solved, he would follow, according to Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg, a certain cooling of the Czech-Indian relations.
The minister said so today in New York, after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not solved, then yes, a certain cooling would occur," he said after the meeting, carried out following a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, after leaving the talks, that the executive branch could hardly intervene in court cases.
He nevertheless mentioned that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was discharged from the charge and punished with a fine, the central government could negotiate with the local government, that of Darjeling, the case being placed under the jurisdiction of the latter.
“His problem could be solved,” the minister said.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for Emil Kučera, sentenced to three years in prison, is to appeal to a higher court.
Therefore, he could seek bail and wait for the trial at large, he explained.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner expressed himself in the same direction also during the talks.
"He advises appealing to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned," the Czech foreign minister said.
The only way, by which the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicted "competent legal support", the Indian minister said.
He also says that such help was already given to them by India.
“Above all, we want to keep with India the best relations, which have a tradition that has continued over many years.
The Indians also acknowledge it,” Schwarzenberg said.
At the same time, as he told ČTK, he pointed out to his partner that the Czech Republic attached great importance to the problem of Czech entomologies.
“We consider the incarceration and accusation of these Czech researchers to be a great mistake,” he said.
The minister dodged the issue if he got the promise from India to deal with the matter.
"I've already received quite a lot of promises," he said.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long distance bus is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the bus of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arises if the stewards and passengers can travel within the bus.
“If we wanted to strictly and formally abide by the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the road traffic law,” said Transportation Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess perished, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the path of the bus.
The girl was at that time unfortunately sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had at her disposal two other seats.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even slow down abruptly, also at the moment when the steward serves coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its technical sheet equipped with standing or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing seats; this has been confirmed in Aktuálně.cz by the director of the company Radim Jančura.
"This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got the passengers to go to the bathroom during the ride provided they had their own seat,” he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal requirement is concerned with this role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement shall prohibit the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transport Act is only known to be the term vehicle catcher; it does not define its rights and duties," said spokesman Hanzelka.
Josef Pokorný, the director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the issue.
"It all depends on whether the bus has in its homologation permission to offer standing places.
Everything is in there,” he said.
Coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing seats and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing seats and higher allowed speed and long-distance coaches without standing with the highest maximum permissible speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"During regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service on airplanes.
There either, it is not safe when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant can hit his head."
"However, in the event that the bus would have braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as on an urban bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards with internal prescriptions," he said, and also said that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jančura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only coach carrier to offer stewards services.
He hires two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their profession as a risky profession.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I feel like it's a risky job, I'll remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper at boarding.
It would also reduce costs,” he said.
The concern for safety is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, who ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses. We have been opposing it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident,” he said, a year ago, to Týden.cz.
A huge tragedy has come
A young hostess from the region of Plzeň, who had been working for the company for two years, perished during the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a flashing and it blocked the way to the bus.
The latter's driver tried to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he brushed him by his right side.
Jančura refuses that the two seats reserved for rest for the stewards have been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the driver of the truck.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but with regard to financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
An amendment to the law?
Not in sight
A change in the law, which has been being developed for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide details on the movement of stewards on board the coach.
"It has not come to any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather on the point system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Hořín.
“The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards to be something that would fundamentally jeopardize the safety of passengers,” said spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the control of bus safety is under the power of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
A Czech referee the fight for the seabed
It approaches a wall-mounted electronic map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are represented.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but at a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is however as large as the continent itself," said Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its leader, the director of the division, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
Work ardour and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a little-known world so far, rich in natural resources.
There can be oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also unknown living organisms, which may contain the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A background larger than the mainland
The coastal states have begun today to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are indeed using their rights, over which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of what is called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the convention, claim exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered a continental shelf.
It extends beyond the boundaries of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred marine miles that represent the said exclusive economic yone,” says Mikulka.
The request submitted by the country in question to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of continental shelf should be supported by extensive scientific-technical documentation, based on many costly prospecting and merit.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical aid.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
For the moment, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful,” Mikulka added.
Australia's success, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently seen a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed allocated to it by the commission last week, is 1.6 million square kilometres, which represents the extent of the country multiplied by sixfold.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they intend, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their request.
They can do so within ten years after ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
Where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no more states have an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area shall be granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike," said director Mikulka, adding that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed also belongs to the Czech Republic today.
It shares it with other states of the former bloc of the countries of the East within the framework of the common organization "Interoceanmetal".
This obtained in 1991, under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other states, the status of the so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right to extract in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and the Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is eventful, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract there on an area with a total area of 75 000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," enumerates Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
