Nights of Insomnia for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word `relatively' and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a credit of one billion to protect itself from the turbulence of the markets.
A person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to an amount of 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
Money comes from both private and public-law banks.
In the background, it is the company-daughter Depfa that bears the losses.
According to a newspaper article, the state financier had refinanced itself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has not been possible since because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, and the own capital rate had also slightly declined from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
The outstanding profits and the net profits from financial transactions were, compared to the same period in the previous year, fallen to point zero, the profits from the allocation of specified debts and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen from more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
And it is only thanks to the large profits derived from the repayment of downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the deficit of gains of about 16 percent has proven to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially misspeculated on industrial mortgages, which had then been subsidiaryized to the bank Aareal.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, the Depfa had then engaged more intensely in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter-story company, the Hypo Real Estate must make depreciation that should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect that remains quite unclear.
The fact is that the dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated two-thirds.
