Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach is fleeing in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he is experiencing the same thing when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of the answers to the question "What do you think you are true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter into difficult-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is facing danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduct a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience to that of animals.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral Cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being even differs from other primates.
Another significant feature could lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness in other animals may look like.
If this, internal and subjective, is not measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzing based on our own experience, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily scientifically accessible.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick have followed, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also emphasizes the weight of the prefrontal Cortex in the realization of the visualization.
But what happens for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the reactions of the body) grips the living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially man.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of the body sensation of the Cortex and the brain stem, as well as Jaak Pankseep, which focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in cross-sectional sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is unbreakable.
Pankseep argues that what is fearful in Men and Rats is probably also felt as such in both cases: how could one nevertheless check whether rats and Men feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach is fleeing in the face of danger, but if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nerve comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain trunks, however, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem causing the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans: how could we demonstrate it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is marked on the nervous plane insofar as the same is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore the language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
One could judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly knocking myself against a wall.
I am indeed a pragmatic emotion.
