William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (died 25 September) states that "in 1946 he had resumed his studies in economic history, at Oxford, and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while he was doing a BSc, an MA and a PhD."
This is what comes from the letter of the author of Woodruff in Beyond Nab End, but this is not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, and at the same time completed a PhD thesis on the British plastic industry, under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers was published in 1958 under the title The British Rubber Industry.
In the 1950s and 51s in the United States, he studied at the Norman Hop, and in the summer of 1952, at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for Illinois.
The reason Woodruff chose to hide that part of his past remains unknown.
