"I photograph the master off the stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no strange clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen looks of artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists, you must not take photos on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera moments of personality of the flamenco stars ".
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recalls classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the singing itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and the magic was the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has evolved into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of collection of portraits exhibited in the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I think that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don’t know or that only leave you a few minutes to be able to give them a photo.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Persolventary of Hercules) which will be open until October 16.
