The novel takes place in places that no one knows and deals with unknown subjects, but once again, Mario Vargas Llosa is determined to advance the new project he is working on, a novel that has as its main character Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who has lived twenty years in Congo and who has passed through the Amazon.
The Nobel Prize winner of Literature confessed yesterday at the Hay festival Segovia, that the novel that currently occupies it "is a real boldness" and that "everything demonstrates that he should not write it".
“If I were reasonable, I wouldn’t, but I’m going to do it and I hope to finish it,” he concluded in his speech at the festival of exchanging ideas and thoughts that for four days saw a hundred writers, historians and journalists and thousands of people march through the city of the aqueduct.
