The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have made this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Research in Advanced Science and Technology at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the managing director of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow vehicles of the brand to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But most importantly, it is the bee’s composed eyes, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a Laser Range Finder.
The latter detects obstacles that are located over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
“At the time it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, "says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Travel Laboratory and the main engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can only be diverted upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
" Every second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of prior maneuvers, which is why it can operate continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This is the first to develop new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last more than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
Alcohol repeat offenders at the wheel will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for blood alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the start of the vehicle intoxicated, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is the rehabilitation of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the Directorate General of Road Safety and the Technological Institute Foundation for Automotive Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once intoxicated, the car resumes.
The alcoholock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infringements during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform made by penal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and function vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in the school buses as it was done in France.
