The interview - Blood returned to safety
Héma-Québec was celebrating yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980’s and 1990’s.
As is well known, the national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service have been contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (AIS) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In the face of this tragedy and public growl, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, an investigation that focused on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and making recommendations to ensure that such a disaster does not happen again.
While Justice Krever was slow to table his report, some provinces then established a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Decary.
The situation was disheartening.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and fieldwork in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation, on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when we do not know and that a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was therefore denied for people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
However, a few years ago, it was proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999 appeared on the market a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing: nucleic acid tests (NATs) that make it possible to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The NATs have shortened the dumb period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to a period of less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowing it and that they will not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people runs the risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, "says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year appeared on the island of Reunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant, "continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for an adequate supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which includes on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person, aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer give blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
The life of today being so frantic, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of his blood, "sorry Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for burn victims.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand per year.
We should start offering some for transplants early next year, "says Dr. Decary who describes this program of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
