Charest bet on the north
The Prime Minister does not rule out triggering elections until the end of the year
As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party was over, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon, Quebec City, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected on the occasion of today's by-election.
"Pushing the boundaries of our last major northern border": this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in broad outline, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was projected a kind of Image Mill.
Turned in a loop, on three huge screens, spectacular shots of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec seen by "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Great resources as during the election period.
In a press briefing, moreover, the Prime Minister refused to rule out that he would call the election this fall, even though he pointed out that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the Prime Minister's speeches recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory in the 49th parallel - had never been presented.
However, the Prime Minister limited himself to explaining why the North was "a jewel with immense potential", but did not give a deadline, amounts of investment, or a precise priority in future projects.
At most a few avenues of what could be further developed: including hydropower, the forest, but especially the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamond", according to the enumeration of M. Charest.
This "territory twice as big as France", "it's home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it home, but it’s in us,” he insisted, as if to show that he was asking for a national founding myth.
Quebec has built a lot in its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
“It’s ours, it’s our future,” he added, after taking a theatrical break to see the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the Prime Minister said at the press briefing.
"This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate this position on behalf of the government," he said.
Moreover, "with climate change, we must rethink our vision of the North," he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open all year round because of the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the people of the territory, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former PQ MP of Ungava), have already begun consultations with about thirty communities.
An inter-ministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important place has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not exclude a great meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a time when "we will give ourselves a common vision".
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Plan Nord will be "concerted, orderly and respectful of the environment," he said.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in continuity with that of the Liberal prime minister who preceded it.
"Like the Liberals who came before us, we thought differently to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development."
This was also one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began Friday with a big cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of the arrival of Jean Lesage at the head of the party.
One of the adopted resolutions proposes to rename the Beauharnois Central to the Adélard-Godbout Dam.
"From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage who made the Revolution quiet and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa who made James Bay, our party was able to forge the future," said Jean Charest.
In a press briefing, he invoked another reference, conservative this one, the program "Roads to the North" of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
By approaching the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, M. Charest noted that its commissioning was scheduled for 2012.
“It stays between us there, but I plan to be there,” he told his activists, arousing applause at home.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of triggering a vote this fall, which the law allows him.
He points out that his schedule is, however, fulfilled, in particular by a mission of the council of the federation in China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend’s General Council provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, including “constitutional aspirations” that have passed like a letter to the post: the PLQ calls in particular for recognition of the “specificity of Quebec” in the Constitution.
He also hoped that Quebec would appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission and that they would have veto power over decisions made in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the outlines of the Plan Nord were welcomed with scepticism.
The PQ leader, Pauline Marois, emerged from the Northern Quebec Development Policy that the Landry government launched in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, coming to power in 2003, gave up implementing it.
If he had done so, "we would be more advanced today" commented Ms. Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (scrutin who is taking place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ supported the government's adoption of a Northern Plan.
"But what we want is for it not to be just a show," commented the leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who is returning from vacation today.
Letters - A disgraced country
It's M. Vic Toews, former Minister of Justice (O irony) in the Harper cabinet, which allowed herself last summer to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "shame" for Canada.
To bring shame on this woman who has fought a tireless fight for justice and who deserves our admiration says as much about the Prime Minister's entourage as it does about Stephen Harper himself.
Here we are in front of a government that is the only one, among all the Western countries involved, not to have repatriated its national locked in the concentration camp of Guantánamo.
A government that ignores the fact that Omar Khadr was a very young teenager at the time of the charges against him.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, denies its word and leaves a child-soldier languishing in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
Recall, for the record, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, among other things, are calling for the repatriation of Omar Khadr to receive a fair trial in Canada.
It is this same government that turns a blind eye to torture: it does not matter that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, probably forever after so many years of abuse.
We do not yet realize it, but we are witnessing at the moment an insidious erosion of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", this word that Harper never ceases to brandish and that sounds so hollow in his mouth.
Now is the time when no morals exist anymore: you can abuse, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen according to the goodwill of a previously minority head of government (what will happen after October 14...).
Many voters believe that they will find salvation in a party that advocates Virtue, the Law and the Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what made the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, M. Toews, she's here, in this renunciation, and not elsewhere.
Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Senior Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Continuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, penny-free publishing house in an effort to launch a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by M. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the Black Book Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look into the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was therefore enough for the miner to open her books, her files and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Maybe Mr. Could Garver explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while despising the opinions of the same audience?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What does not understand - or does not want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who support the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it above all because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag suit (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice to the authors of Black Canada telling them to stop the use of this term...).
Beyond Mr.'s surreal speech Garver, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to the quotation of credible sources and the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms that limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Get Along
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 30’s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of review on the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The time limit that had been granted was the opening of the markets this morning.
Late associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, without failing, however, to express their discontent that one is obliged to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has agreed to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow owners to keep their homes and the salary of the executives of companies rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to welcome.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television.
Asked on another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outlines I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the bad, risk-asset and unsaleable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprime) before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a freeze on liquidity and the disbanding of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who had collapsed the first draft of agreement last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been overcome since the Democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, it was also added a provision stating that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which will be added another 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion is expected to be approved by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will obtain stakes in rescued companies that will earn it dividends in the event of profit and that it can resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing attached to the mortgages covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance pay paid to the executives of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see him submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told its constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists in taking advantage of taxpayers.”
Host of a small group in Congress nicknamed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully examine the path to be taken,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up acquiring its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (US$2.9 billion) in the crisis of risky mortgages in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, we get a right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that times are looking uncertain.”
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank plagued by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all loans in progress at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of mortgages.
Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and accounts receivable of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government would have to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time his card asset, some will say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the source will also have removed him from the register of power that gives birth to the real sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, who disappeared Friday, at the age of 83, from lung cancer on his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of American cinema in the pompous years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of which he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also apostle of freedom and the break-up of dramatic conventions.
The mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother of origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without disproportionate ego, ultimate mark of quality.
Because in him projected himself a whole country in love with the self-made man, of the fighter of the Pacific war, wounded in battle, which in the early 50's studied drama at Yale and then frequented the Actor's Studio of New York, before triumphing in the theater, on television, soon in cinema.
The same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the car driver who ranked second in the 24 hours of Le Mans in 1979, coupled with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadows of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the bursts of show business, whose enigma will not have been quite pierced.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman gave the dizziness to moviegoers this weekend, as his big roles on the black screen of memories clash.
More than half a century of a seventh ever-changing American art marche through it.
Return to shake up the charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Pussy on a Burning Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
So many other Paul Newman have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, taken after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter pool player and avenger in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he will take the character from the return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar on nine nominations in 1987.
That face through the ages was him.
He's still.
The eras are jostling through his journey.
The young people know him especially through the cult Slap Shot of George Roy Hill (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in the Coen brothers' The Hudsucker Proxy.
With a final role as Irish mafia sponsor in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
Against several film legends who let go of the trade early on, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, his golds, his pomp and his concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" judging his performances too strong.
The profession has not always been tender for the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles fell for a long time all cooked in the beak.
He played, however, less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed poorly known facets of his true modest sensitivity.
Her Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (after the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine feminine portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott by overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes that broke yesterday on Newman, his great boyfriend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) claimed, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant features of the missing actor.
Beyond his legendary career, a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of Hollywood drifts also disappears.
We will have seen a lot of his binette throne on pots of vinaigrette, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process of rather bad taste, although gag at first.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Difficulty.
Newman, rather than sitting on his myth, will be committed to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: “Always and until the end, your father has been incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be there.”
And a privilege for us to have followed the journey of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Citizen model, in short and extra.
What could Zuschlag &amp; Company manufacture in their bill factory?
Soon, on 8 October, hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, permanently and regularly, having resulted in particularly significant damage. Other charges were laid against them, such as for example, for false and use of forgery.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false bills.
The money of the state and municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices of expenses, behind which no real benefit was provided and thus, the associations never respected their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the company names that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to spot pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among other things, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the subsidies.
During a "lockdown circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place has ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place, at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will then bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was teeming with misforms and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the invoice mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
The issuers of bills with an overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounting, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of the Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor's office summoned him and showed him the bills, he knew, right away, that these were fake documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people have stayed there, did not stick either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not inquire about the travel agencies of Budapest, being part of their choice, but organizing only trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
Moreover, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the services concerning travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are charged without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up on behalf of the Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not support a 25% VAT as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, the hotel employees only issue printed bills, while the fakes were handwritten.
The investigation by the public prosecutor's office reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in mentioning as a service the transport of goods by road, that the company issuing invoices could not exercise, since its profile was investment advice.
Moreover, it is also for defects of forms, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont have proven to be false.
Just as in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports course, which both deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestrét Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the grouping of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has established an invoice to the order of the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of about five million
No financial move took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this, the organizations did avoid mentioning it in their accounting.
The next category of invoice companies is that of companies directly related to accused persons.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the managing director of the company Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he was not found there, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, for an amount of about 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, this equipment was purchased by the company Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
From what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to the orders of Atlasz, Hoppá and de Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were operating, which the accused explains by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-defendant as well as editor of the founding acts of the companies, he established invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov has given organizations, 15 invoices in total, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of 14.2 million HUF.
The prosecutor's office thought that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as the VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used as part of the Biztos Pont grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant from the public utility organization of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant for twice 500,000 HUFs, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To prevent this from being known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, it was these invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will report the method of manufacturing the invoices, as it had already done before the public prosecutor's office previously.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
