The psychology of bidding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have successfully updated the neurological and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be out of date during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers were analyzing the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the outbidding of a third party, the whole being under the brainstem, called striatum, switched in intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers have pursued financial monitoring analyses.
During these, three groups outbid against a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus carried out their stake.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out of the game winner, then they would receive an additional 15 dollars, as a reward.
While the third group received these 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the focus was on one victory, while in the other, on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, the professor at the New York University School of Economics, found.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that the disease has hepatitis virus in Hungary is estimated to be a hundred miles, but only seven miles are undergoing treatment. This is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach upset and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes on a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know that they have the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakily destroys the cells of the liver. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after the age of 20 to 30.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Confectionation is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis type C are in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine examination in the laboratory, it is advisable to consult his attending physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of a cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
