Smart cars mimic the theft of the drone
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, the bee.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan’s strategic initial idea to engineers to inspire them on how they need to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-roboticized control system, of the BR23C type, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its thefts, each bee is its own space, oval in shape, which in reality, is very similar to our secure protective hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand.
The bee's faceted eye plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers addressed the idea of the laser rangefinder.
The latter identifies obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot auto, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t so, the mini robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, in place of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration and the slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini robot auto
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and with a larger energy concentrate, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We do not need memory of a capacity of gigabytes, or even of megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding the obstacles in his path.
