A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs which link the use of information concerning the prescription of medicinal products, in any case, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it amounts to entrusting his chicken coop to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital depend in the event of damage, the state of health of the client who presents himself, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after becoming aware of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains data from pharmacies, data concerning the purchase of drugs from the person in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines for itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is their state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high fat level in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a coefficient of risk, therefore, there is not much left to do to the insurer except for paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers to be an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must request permission from the patient before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also dealt with laboratory test results, and link them with data on drug use. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of usage is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the expansion of the control circle of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his agreement or not, since if he refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus and ultimately, the chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
