In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena incubated for some time, so much so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the double category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, obviously closely with the foreigner, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is to say, as to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems to be really out of the game or, has little to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union, which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all expect interventions, bailouts and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit condition: when we go through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimization to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements which no market or international organization can ever dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the state-nation crisis is moreover in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, ever more sophisticated technology, non-material technology, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once, that on the contrary our future will have to settle its scores always more with things rather unmaterial such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly possesses more cards than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, state, government, inevitably says Political, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of a shadowy area.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, a picture of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of countries of the West.
Thus further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
in short, the demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised "revolts" electoral or, in the changes of collective moods of recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, at the fall of the Labours in Great Britain, in the rebellion of the American congressmen
