But it is said, keeping your eyes wide open is not without reason.
The supercolla to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measured just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body stuck on a vertical wall.
The American Journal Science published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti." Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that make it possible to assure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "easily detaches from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton School of Engineering.
WALKING ON THE WALLS? –” this material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conducting heat and electric current.
Other applications may be related to aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented an adhesive made up of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on an area to ensure perfect and constant adherence.
