Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in the summer because it is non-altering and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital drugs, alter the amplifying or decreasing absorption according to the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether in box or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm: it only takes a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice, to reduce the absorption of certain drugs.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized because it is responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-staminal and neurological drugs, to toxic levels.
A RISK- It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a two-year newsletter, alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger arising from this mix and to pay attention to what is being done, if we take drugs such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT JUST THE GRAPeFRU. According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the call of Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan: "These discoveries are generally, immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the informational notes of the drugs if necessary.
