Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying on the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Neva Nevada border.
Inside the plane, no human remains though.
Madera County's sheriff, John Anderson, ousted the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is indeed the one on which Steve Fosset was traveling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said that no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) said that a few hours after the wreckage was found, a team of investigators sent to the scene, identified the aircraft: it is indeed the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he became in 2002, the first man to complete the round the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had traveled the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
