Historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-halls, and the death of consumption of single-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if a friend of mine disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a piece of path and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prize of the juror of Cannes, and who told the poetry of a cinema.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have mainly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Roman Emilia is in the lead with 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms and that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is indeed the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-hall cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian farm has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplexes.
