When the energy is born of the waves, now the bigs launch.
This is an disproportionate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's area and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossi like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now try to get their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 70's, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now environmental authorities and the new increase in oil are giving the sector a great boost
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the global electricity need could be covered by seaswell operating systems.
This quantity would be double that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was the Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it would have been said a real revolutionary step.
Two years from this, more and more candidates among these companies, always dedicated to traditional energy, are betting on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies – said the spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant, to the business daily Wall Street Journal – and it is evaluating the possibilities of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question, concerns the obtaining of a permit deliberated by the American Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that in Alaska, the Usa continue to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for new excavations
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. From New York and Ocean Power to New Jersey, which are running the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested to the present day, although their details are not known, according to observers, is of increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about technology still in its early days, because marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a superior environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the sludge upwards and downwards, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn, supplies a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
For the time being, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, already produces energy for a shopping center and parking using six underwater turbines from the East River of New York.
The movement of water during tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for the Research of Electrical Energy, deserves at the moment, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from the wind, the sun, or the waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, have invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and expects investments up to 35 million in 2009.
